In {{ill|Tenshō|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|12=draft}}18th year ({{ill|1590|ja|1590|12=draft}}), following the entry of {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|12=draft}} into Edo, the {{ill|Portable Shrine|ja|神輿|12=draft}} of Hie Shrine was enshrined here. The location of the enshrinement is called {{ill|Otabi-sho|ja|御旅所|12=draft}}. Even today, during the Sannō Festival held every other year, the portable shrine and {{ill|Dashi|ja|山車|12=draft}} make a tour between the main shrine and this shrine<ref name="日本橋摂社">[http://www.hiejinjanihombashisessha.tokyo/venerable.php Venerable history and enshrined deities] Nihonbashi Hie Shrine</ref>{{Sfn|Masayoshi Kanayama|Rumi Kanayama|1993|p=63}}.

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft}}, {{ill|Chisenin|ja|智泉院 (東京都中央区)|lt=Chisenin|lt_ja=智泉院|12=draft}} served as the head temple ({{ill|Bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|12=draft}}) of this shrine; however, in the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|12=draft}}, due to the separation of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft}}), it was detached from this shrine. Subsequently, with the elevation in status of the main Hie Shrine, this shrine was also reorganized.<ref name="日本橋摂社"></ref>

==Access==
*{{ill|Kayabacho Station|ja|茅場町駅|12=draft}} (1 minute walk).

