'''Nihonbashi Hie Shrine''' (日枝神社日本橋摂社) is a {{ill|Shrine|ja|神社}} located in {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京都}} {{ill|Chūō Ward, Tokyo|ja|中央区 (東京都)|lt=Chūō|lt_ja=中央区}} {{ill|Nihonbashi Kayabacho|ja|日本橋茅場町}}. It is the external {{ill|Sessha|ja|摂末社|lt=Sessha|lt_ja=摂社}} of the {{ill|Hie Shrine|ja|日枝神社 (千代田区)|lt=Hie Shrine|lt_ja=日枝神社}} in {{ill|Chiyoda Ward|ja|千代田区}} {{ill|Nagatachō|ja|永田町}}.
It is also called '''Nihonbashi Hie Shrine'''.

==History==
In {{ill|Tenshō|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era}}18th year ({{ill|1590|ja|1590}}), following the entry of {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康}} into Edo, the {{ill|Portable Shrine|ja|神輿}} of Hie Shrine was enshrined here. The location of the enshrinement is called {{ill|Otabi-sho|ja|御旅所}}. Even today, during the Sannō Festival held every other year, the portable shrine and {{ill|Dashi|ja|山車}} make a tour between the main shrine and this shrine<ref name="日本橋摂社">[http://www.hiejinjanihombashisessha.tokyo/venerable.php Venerable history and enshrined deities] Nihonbashi Hie Shrine</ref>{{Sfn|Masayoshi Kanayama|Rumi Kanayama|1993|p=63}}.

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}}, {{ill|Chisenin|ja|智泉院 (東京都中央区)|lt=Chisenin|lt_ja=智泉院}} served as the head temple ({{ill|Bettō-ji|ja|別当寺}}) of this shrine; however, in the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代}}, due to the separation of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離}}), it was detached from this shrine. Subsequently, with the elevation in status of the main Hie Shrine, this shrine was also reorganized.<ref name="日本橋摂社"></ref>

==Access==
*{{ill|Kayabacho Station|ja|茅場町駅}} (1 minute walk).

