'''Nihonbashi Hie Shrine''' (日枝神社日本橋摂社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shrine]] located in [[:en:Tokyo|Tokyo]] [[:en:Chūō, Tokyo|Chūō]] {{ill|Nihonbashi Kayabacho|ja|日本橋茅場町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihonbashi Kayabacho|qq=}}. It is the external [[:en:Setsumatsusha|Sessha]] of the [[:en:Hie Shrine|Hie Shrine]] in [[:en:Chiyoda, Tokyo|Chiyoda Ward]] [[:en:Nagatachō|Nagatachō]].
It is also called '''Nihonbashi Hie Shrine'''.

==History==
In [[:en:Tenshō (Momoyama period)|Tenshō Era]]18th year ({{ill|1590|ja|1590|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1590|qq=}}), following the entry of [[:en:Tokugawa Ieyasu|Tokugawa Ieyasu]] into Edo, the [[:en:Mikoshi|Portable Shrine]] of Hie Shrine was enshrined here. The location of the enshrinement is called [[:en:Otabisho|Otabi-sho]]. Even today, during the Sannō Festival held every other year, the portable shrine and [[:en:Matsuri float|Dashi]] make a tour between the main shrine and this shrine<ref name="日本橋摂社">[http://www.hiejinjanihombashisessha.tokyo/venerable.php Venerable history and enshrined deities] Nihonbashi Hie Shrine</ref>{{Sfn|Masayoshi Kanayama|Rumi Kanayama|1993|p=63}}.

During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], {{ill|Chisenin|ja|智泉院 (東京都中央区)|lt=Chisenin|lt_ja=智泉院|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chisenin|qq=}} served as the head temple ({{ill|Bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bettō-ji|qq=}}) of this shrine; however, in the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji period]], due to the separation of Shinto and Buddhism ([[:en:Shinbutsu bunri|Shinbutsu bunri]]), it was detached from this shrine. Subsequently, with the elevation in status of the main Hie Shrine, this shrine was also reorganized.<ref name="日本橋摂社"></ref>

==Access==
*[[:en:Kayabachō Station|Kayabacho Station]] (1 minute walk).

