==History==
In {{ill|Tenshō (Momoyama period)|en|Tenshō (Momoyama period)|WD=Q1145058|lt=Tenshō Era|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}}18th year ({{ill|1590|en|1590|WD=Q6764|lt=1590|1=1590}}), following the entry of {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|en|Tokugawa Ieyasu|WD=Q171977|lt=Tokugawa Ieyasu|1=Tokugawa Ieyasu}} into Edo, the {{ill|Mikoshi|en|Mikoshi|WD=Q979940|lt=Portable Shrine|1=Mikoshi}} of Hie Shrine was enshrined here. The location of the enshrinement is called {{ill|Otabisho|en|Otabisho|WD=Q11489117|lt=Otabi-sho|1=Otabisho}}. Even today, during the Sannō Festival held every other year, the portable shrine and {{ill|Matsuri float|en|Matsuri float|WD=Q11470974|lt=Dashi|1=Matsuri float}} make a tour between the main shrine and this shrine<ref name="日本橋摂社">[http://www.hiejinjanihombashisessha.tokyo/venerable.php Venerable history and enshrined deities] Nihonbashi Hie Shrine</ref>{{Sfn|Masayoshi Kanayama|Rumi Kanayama|1993|p=63}}.

During the {{ill|Edo period|en|Edo period|WD=Q184963|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period}}, {{ill|Chisenin|ja|智泉院 (東京都中央区)|lt=Chisenin|lt_ja=智泉院|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chisenin|1=Chisen-in Temple|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q106836711}} served as the head temple ({{ill|Bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bettō-ji|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}) of this shrine; however, in the {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|WD=Q3125096|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era}}, due to the separation of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|en|Shinbutsu bunri|WD=Q1970535|lt=Shinbutsu bunri|1=Shinbutsu bunri}}), it was detached from this shrine. Subsequently, with the elevation in status of the main Hie Shrine, this shrine was also reorganized.<ref name="日本橋摂社"></ref>

==Access==
*{{ill|Kayabachō Station|en|Kayabachō Station|WD=Q80566|lt=Kayabacho Station|1=Kayabachō Station}} (1 minute walk).

